<subSubSection box="[828,1388,1365,1390]" pageId="54" pageNumber="2836" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="54.[826,1467,1286,1956]" box="[828,1388,1365,1390]" pageId="54" pageNumber="2836">
<taxonomicName authorityName="Zheng &amp; Wittouck &amp; Salvetti &amp; Franz &amp; Harris &amp; Mattarelli &amp; O’Toole &amp; Pot &amp; Vandamme &amp; Walter &amp; Watanabe &amp; Wuyts &amp; Felis &amp; Gänzle &amp; Lebeer" authorityYear="2020" baseAuthorityName="Zheng &amp; Wittouck &amp; Salvetti &amp; Franz &amp; Harris &amp; Mattarelli &amp; O’Toole &amp; Pot &amp; Vandamme &amp; Walter &amp; Watanabe &amp; Wuyts &amp; Felis &amp; Gänzle &amp; Lebeer" baseAuthorityYear="2020" box="[828,1068,1366,1390]" class="Bacilli" family="Lactobacillaceae" genus="Levilactobacillus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Bacteria" order="Lactobacillales" pageId="54" pageNumber="2836" phylum="Firmicutes" rank="species" species="brevis">
<emphasis box="[828,1068,1366,1390]" italics="true" pageId="54" pageNumber="2836">Levilactobacillus brevis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(bre′ vis. L. adj. brevis short).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="54" pageNumber="2836" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="54.[826,1467,1286,1956]" pageId="54" pageNumber="2836">
Basonym: 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Bergey et al." authorityYear="1934" baseAuthorityName="Orla-Jensen" baseAuthorityYear="1919" box="[945,1157,1413,1437]" class="Bacilli" family="Lactobacillaceae" genus="Lactobacillus" kingdom="Bacteria" order="Lactobacillales" pageId="54" pageNumber="2836" phylum="Firmicutes" rank="species" species="brevis">
<emphasis box="[945,1157,1413,1437]" italics="true" pageId="54" pageNumber="2836">Lactobacillus brevis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<emphasis box="[1176,1397,1413,1437]" italics="true" pageId="54" pageNumber="2836">Betabacterium breve</emphasis>
Orla-Jensen 1919, 175) Bergey 
<emphasis box="[1100,1144,1444,1468]" italics="true" pageId="54" pageNumber="2836">et al</emphasis>
. 1934, 312 (Approved Lists)
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="54.[826,1467,1286,1956]" pageId="54" pageNumber="2836">
The species was described in [
<bibRefCitation author="Orla-Jensen S." box="[1166,1182,1491,1515]" pageId="54" pageNumber="2836" refId="ref59849" refString="2. Orla-Jensen S. The lactic acid bacteria. Copenhagen: Andr Fred HOst and Son; 1919." type="book" year="1919">2</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation author="Bergey DH &amp; Breed RS &amp; Hammer BW &amp; Huntoon FM &amp; Murray EGD" box="[1196,1241,1491,1515]" pageId="54" pageNumber="2836" refId="ref72539" refString="289. Bergey DH, Breed RS, Hammer BW, Huntoon FM, Murray EGD et al. Bergey's Manual of Determinative Bacteriology, 4 th ed. Baltimore: The Williams &amp; Wilkins Co; 1934." type="book" year="1934">289</bibRefCitation>
]. Strains of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Bergey et al." authorityYear="1934" baseAuthorityName="Orla-Jensen" baseAuthorityYear="1919" box="[1374,1467,1491,1515]" class="Bacilli" family="Lactobacillaceae" genus="Lactobacillus" kingdom="Bacteria" order="Lactobacillales" pageId="54" pageNumber="2836" phylum="Firmicutes" rank="species" species="brevis">
<emphasis box="[1374,1467,1491,1515]" italics="true" pageId="54" pageNumber="2836">L. brevis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
widely occur in vegetable and cereal fermentations and as beer-spoilage organisms and were also isolated from insects. Niche adaptation is mediated by acquisition of plasmids [
<bibRefCitation author="Fraunhofer ME &amp; Geissler AJ &amp; Behr J &amp; Vogel RF" box="[834,880,1618,1642]" pageId="54" pageNumber="2836" pagination="37 - 47" refId="ref72578" refString="290. Fraunhofer ME, Geissler AJ, Behr J, Vogel RF. Comparative genomics of Lactobacillus brevis reveals a significant plasmidome overlap of brewery and insect isolates. Curr Microbiol 2019; 76: 37 - 47." type="journal article" year="2019">290</bibRefCitation>
]. The genome size of the 
<typeStatus box="[1160,1206,1618,1642]" pageId="54" pageNumber="2836">type</typeStatus>
strain is 2.47 Mbp. The mol% G+C content of DNA is 46.0.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="54.[826,1467,1286,1956]" pageId="54" pageNumber="2836">Isolated from milk, cheese, sauerkraut and rrelated vegetable fermentations, sourdough, silage, cow manure, faeces, and the mouth and intestinal tract of humans and rats.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
